Strings in Java are one of the most commonly used classes. They represent sequences of characters and are **immutable**, 
meaning once created, they cannot be changed.
## 1. Creating Strings
// Using string literal
String s1 = "Hello";
// Using new keyword
String s2 = new String("World");
String literals are stored in the String pool for memory efficiency.
new String() always creates a new object in heap memory.

2. String Immutability
java
String s = "Hello";
s.concat(" World");
System.out.println(s); // Output: Hello
The original string s remains unchanged.
A new string "Hello World" is created but not assigned.

3. Common Methods
Length
String s = "Java";
System.out.println(s.length()); // 4
Character Access
String s = "Java";
System.out.println(s.charAt(2)); // 'v'
Substring
String s = "Programming";
System.out.println(s.substring(0, 6)); // "Progra"
IndexOf
String s = "mississippi";
System.out.println(s.indexOf("issip")); // 4
Equals vs ==
String s1 = "Hello";
String s2 = "Hello";
String s3 = new String("Hello");
System.out.println(s1 == s2);      // true (same pool reference)
System.out.println(s1 == s3);      // false (different object)
System.out.println(s1.equals(s3)); // true (same content)

4. String Comparison
String a = "apple";
String b = "banana";
System.out.println(a.compareTo(b)); // negative (apple < banana)
System.out.println(b.compareTo(a)); // positive (banana > apple)
System.out.println(a.compareTo("apple")); // 0 (equal)

5. String Concatenation
String s1 = "Hello";
String s2 = "World";
String result = s1 + " " + s2;
System.out.println(result); // "Hello World"
The + operator internally uses StringBuilder for efficiency.

6. StringBuilder and StringBuffer
StringBuilder: Mutable, faster, not thread‑safe.
StringBuffer: Mutable, thread‑safe (synchronized).
StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder("Hello");
sb.append(" World");
System.out.println(sb); // "Hello World"

7. Useful Methods
String s = "  Java Programming  ";
// Trim
System.out.println(s.trim()); // "Java Programming"
// To Upper/Lower Case
System.out.println(s.toUpperCase()); // "  JAVA PROGRAMMING  "
System.out.println(s.toLowerCase()); // "  java programming  "
// Replace
System.out.println(s.replace("Java", "Python")); // "  Python Programming  "
// Split
String[] parts = s.trim().split(" ");
for (String part : parts) {
    System.out.println(part);
}
// Output:
// Java
// Programming

8. String Pool
Strings created with literals are stored in a pool.
Reuses existing objects to save memory.
String s1 = "Hello";
String s2 = "Hello";
System.out.println(s1 == s2); // true (same pool reference)

9. Performance Notes
Use StringBuilder for heavy concatenation in loops.
String is best for fixed text values.
StringBuffer is useful in multithreaded environments.

10. Summary
Strings are immutable.
Use .equals() for content comparison.
Prefer StringBuilder for modifications.
String pool optimizes memory usage.
